evaluation.response:
Bummer about the B+ on the calc quiz! It's clear that was frustrating for you. And that comment on your test paper from Mr. Abbott can be tough to see. It's like, your teachers are aware that they have so much pull over their students' lives, but not always enough to actually help and support you when you really need it.

Mr. Abbott didn't mean it like that of course, but it's like he's implying you shouldn't have gotten those questions wrong—it's too frustrating.

You said you didn't want to have to explain what's going on. I get it. It feels like when you're not performing perfectly, everyone's like, "Oh, what's wrong?" As if this is some permanent thing. And sometimes that can be uncomfortable or overwhelming. But what if you actually talked to Mr. Abbott about this? What if you told him you're just having a bit of a rough patch? That doesn't have to be a sophisticated conversation. You could just be like, "Yeah, I'm just feeling a little burnt out lately. That's all." But maybe try signaling that you're okay and don't need to talk about your grade or whatever.&#x20;
